03883nam a22005295i 9780773552319DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735523197 a10.1515/97807735523192doi  a(DE-B1597)657648  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aK370b.C63 2017 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a340/.1152231 aCochran, Patricia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommon Sense and Legal Judgment :bCommunity Knowledge, Political Power, and Rhetorical Practice /cPatricia Cochran. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCommon Sense: Self-evident and Inscrutable -- tThomas Reid s Common Sense: Accountability for Judgment and the Boundaries of Debate -- tAntonio Gramsci’s Common Sense: History, Power, and Our Conception of the World -- tHannah Arendt’s Common Sense: Imagining Communities and the Basis of Valid Judgment -- tConclusion: Common Sense for Good Legal Judgment -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean when a judge in a court of law uses the phrase “common sense”? Is it a type of evidence or a mode of reasoning? In a world characterized by material and political inequalities, whose common sense should inform the law? Common Sense and Legal Judgment explores this rhetorically powerful phrase, arguing that common sense, when invoked in political and legal discourses without adequate reflection, poses a threat to the quality and legitimacy of legal judgment. Often operating in the service of conservatism, populism, or majoritarianism, common sense can harbour stereotypes, reproduce unjust power relations, and silence marginalized people. Nevertheless, drawing the works of theorists such as Thomas Reid, Antonio Gramsci, and Hannah Arendt into conversation with rulings by the Supreme Court of Canada, Patricia Cochran demonstrates that with careful attention, the democratic, egalitarian, and community-sustaining aspects of common sense can be brought to light. A call for critical self-reflection and the close scrutiny of power relationships and social contexts, this book is a direct response to social justice predicaments and their confounding relationships to law. Creative and interdisciplinary, Common Sense and Legal Judgment reinvigorates feminist and anti-poverty understandings of judgment, knowledge, justice, and accountability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommon sense. 0aJudgment. 0aJustice. 0aLawxPolitical aspects. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 70(DE-601)1056401230(DE-588)4138783-1aGerichtsentscheidung2gnd 70(DE-601)1061243150(DE-588)4064317-7aWahrnehmung2gnd 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773552319?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773552319423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773552319/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles